\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For ease of notation we the distribution of households age 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\{\omega_{25},...\omega_{80}\}$
\end_inset

 ,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the share of the population at age 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We drop the 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 subscript for simplicity.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The political-economic equilibrium of this model consists of value functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ V_{j}^{rent}\left(\mathbf{s};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right),V_{j}^{adjust}\left(\mathbf{s}_{};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right),V_{j}^{non-adjust}\left(\mathbf{s}_{};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 decision rules over the consumption,
 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\mathbf{s};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
 housing demand,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ h^{rent}\left(\mathbf{s};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right),h\left(\mathbf{s};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

,
 liquid savings 
\begin_inset Formula $a\left(\mathbf{s};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
 and votes over housing supply,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(\mathbf{s};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which define the households' optimal allocations as a function of their individual state variables and the aggregate price of housing,
 and the price of housing and rental units which in turn is a function of the distribution of the households' age 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{rent}\left(\Omega\right)$
\end_inset

.
 After calibrating the age distribution of households across the model we set the formation of new households to keep the demographic structure constant (in the absence of demographic shocks).
 Finally we assume households expectations of the future path of house prices follow a random walk and thus in expectation will remain at their current level - at least with respect to the demographic changes in the model.
 The distribution of households,
 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(\mathbf{s};p^{h}\left(\Omega\right)\right)$
\end_inset

,
 is thus defined by the deterministic age and income processes,
 the stochastic income shocks and their optimal choices in response to these shocks.
 The full numerical computational method is outlined in detail in the Appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Calibration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We calibrate the model to capture salient features of the US housing market in the early 2000s prior to the housing boom and bust.
 The model period is one year,
 households work for 41 periods (age 25 to 65) and die after 56 periods (age 80).
 The risk aversion parameter is set to 2,
 as is standard in the macroeconomics literature.
 The income process consists of the parameters for the deterministic age-profile,
 the persistent AR(1) component,
 and the transitory i.i.d.
 component of income.
 We estimate the parameters of the deterministic and stochastic 20 income processes using data from the Panel Study of Income Dynamics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The retirement income replacement rate is set at 50% of the final period's non-transitory income,
 based on Díaz et al.
 (2008).
 The risk-free interest rate is set at 2%,
 while the mortgage interest rate is 5%.
 The maximum loan-to-value (LTV) is set at 0.9 in line with Greenwald (2018).
 The spread between the saving rate and the mortgage rate is set at 3% matching the 30 year average difference between the two.
\end_layout

