\begin_layout Subsection
Impulse Response Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this next section we calculate the dynamics of a demographic shock to the housing market in the form of a temporary baby boom.
 We start the model in its equilibrium and then increase the birthrate of new households by 10 per cent for 10 years as shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Figure 7"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 After 25 years,
 when those who were born during the boom enter the labor and housing market,
 the effect of the spike in the birthrate starts to affect the demographic structure of households in the model.
 We then calculate the equilibrium response of the economy across the subsequent 80 years to see the effect of the baby boom through time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Initially,
 the generation that was born during the boom,
 decreases the median age of households within the economy as the number of young household increases.
 After 10 years the population boom ends and the birth rate returns to normal.
 After the birthrate returns to its steady state level,
 the generation born during the boom continues to age,
 pushing the average age above it's steady state level until they all die out 65 years after they enter the economy and housing market.
 This generation,
 being larger than the generations that come before or after them,
 have disproportionately more voting power.
 The impact of this electorally powerful cohort will vary depending on how the preferences of those born during the boom differ from the rest of the population.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When young,
 those born during the boom are disproportionately renters,
 with lower incomes and lower net wealth.
 As a result they use their outsized voting power to increase the supply of new houses and push down the price of housing.
 The lower price of housing increases the homeownership rate across all ages,
 although the impact on the overall home ownership rate is small.
 In general equilibrium this downward pressure on the price of housing is partially offset by the creation of new home owners who on average prefer higher prices once they purchase a home.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The impact of this initial change in the housing market is to decrease both the level of across-generation inequality (as older and wealthier households relative net worth falls with house prices) and within generational inequality (as renters of all ages are able to either gain access to the housing market for the first time or alternatively pay a lower rate of rent).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However this impact is short lived.
 Greater political support for lower house prices ends after 20 years and prices then rise to above their steady state level.
 This reversal is driven by the increase in homeownership as the boom generation ages.
 The higher rate of homeownership and increases the number of households who expect to be net-sellers of housing and thus would prefer a higher price.
 This rise in home ownership is driven by two effects.
 The first is purely mechanical:
 homeownership rates increase with age as households build up their wealth and the generation born during the boom is comparatively large.
 Hence,
 we would expect an increase in the aggregate homeownership rate of the entire population as this outsized generation ages.
 The second effect is the endogenous impact of the vote to lower house prices in the first 20 years.
 This increased support for higher housing supply in the first two decades makes it easier for households to buy housing across 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 generations.
 Not only do those born during the boom have disproportionate voting power,
 but by initially supporting lower house prices they (unintentionally) increased the size of their future voting coalition across generations by creating more homeowners among the households who are older.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example,
 consider an older,
 low income household that was born 25 years before the baby boom.
 As a low income household they might optimally choose to rent for the entirety of their life.
 However,
 when those born during the boom starts to vote for lower house prices,
 their optimal decision may change allowing them to purchase housing for the first time.
 This change in their status from being a renter to a homeowner (who is unlikely to make additional purchases of housing) will lead them to switch their political support from lower to higher prices for the rest of their life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This rise in house prices,
 however,
 leads to falls in the homeownership rates across all age levels.
 It also more then unwinds the decrease in generational inequality as the wealth ratio of 55-65 year olds to 25-35 year olds increases.
 The generation that is born after the baby boom face a housing market in which house prices are significantly higher.
 This leads them to have a lower rate of home ownership compared with the model's steady state.
 These high house prices persist for several decades those born during the boom start to die.
\emph on

