 Those born during the boom are generally able to use their outsized political power to increase their relative net-worth across the entire life cycle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This demographic shock also affects the generations that come before and after the boom.
 The generation of parents that gave birth to those during the boom are initially worse off when house prices fall.
 However,
 they benefit towards the end of their life when their off-spring transition into homeownership and lift the equilibrium house price.
 The generation of children that came after are rendered permanently poorer due to the higher cost of housing,
 this leads them to have a permanently lower level of net worth across their entire life.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This mechanism outlines how the political economy mechanism of housing supply means that changes in the size of demographic structure can have significant effects on the housing market and economic outcomes for different generations.
\end_layout

