\begin_layout Section*
Appendix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerical solution for our model follows these steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The household's value functions are solve recursively for a fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{h}$
\end_inset

 starting at tin the final period of life and working backwards using equations (8) - (11).
 This provides solutions for the household value functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ V_{j}^{rent},V_{j}^{adjust},V_{j}^{non-adjust}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and the resulting decision rules for consumption,
 housing and liquid assets as a function of the households idiosyncratic state variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The rental price of housing is pinned down by the cost of housing 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{h}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We then calculate how these value functions change if we permanently increase the price of housing by a small amount,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 The difference in the value functions is used to calculate the preferences over housing supply across households,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Next we solve for the density of households across the life cycle using this decision rules to solve for the distribution of households across the idiosyncratic state variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We then use these solutions to calculate the net-support for housing supply which is defined the integrating the density of households over their preferences for housing supply.
 If the net support is close to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

 we stop here,
 if the net support for housing supply is higher (lower) than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5$
\end_inset

 we lower (increase) the assumed price of housing in step 1 and repeat the process until the median voter equation is satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Once the housing market has been 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cleared
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by the political process,
 we iterate forward one period updating the age of each household and repeat the steps 1 through 5.
\end_layout

